default2.  
defaultThe issue of ownership of publicly-funded schools is hardly ever debated.  To whom do – and should – schools funded by the public purse belong?   In past 
defaultperiods 
defaultthis may not have been a major concern.  For example politicians in the post-war period attempted to develop 
defaulteducation 
defaultpolicy largely by consensus, as illustrated 
defaultby 
defaultthe three great reports from the Central Advisory Council (
defaultEngland
default) between 1959 
default(Crowther
default) 
defaultand 1967
default (Plowden).  2013 marks
default the 50
defaultth
default anniversary of the second of these – the Newsom report on the education of 13 to 16 year olds of average and below average ability
default – and like the others it provided a model of how to achieve 
defaultwidespread understand
defaulting of a set of educational challenges and substantial agreement on ways forward.
default  Actual policy tended to be negotiated between the central education department, the associations representing the local education author
defaultities and the teachers’ unions.  It w
defaultas 
defaulta corporatist approach which 
defaultis out of fashion today
default.  Even if it tended towards excessive ambiguity and diffuseness 
defaultand perhaps exaggerated the degree of consensus 
defaultit 
defaulthad the merit of taking into account some key 
defaultstakeholder 
defaultinterests and experience ou
defaulttside central government.
