default&#xa0;defaultEXECUTIVE SUMMARYdefault&#xa0;defaultThe status and image of independent schooling exert a powerful influence on the public imagination and this has encouraged politicians to seek to mimic the governance structure of the English private school in state-funded schooling, 
defaultmost notably in relation to academies.
default  Autonomy is not as simple a concept as is often implied and key questions about it are: autonomy over what and for whom?
default&#xa0;
defaultThe centre has secured ever greater control to impose its preferences about school structure, 
defaultcurriculum and assessment on our large and complex system.  
defaultThere is a significant and growing democratic deficit indicating a crisis of legitimacy.
default&#xa0;
default‘Governance by contract’ 
defaultin relation to academies 
defaultraises 
defaultserious 
defaultissues of public accountability
default and ca
defaultnnot be operated at the very large scale intended without major risks
default.
default  The aim should be to phase this system out as existing agreements come to the end of their life.  In the meantime an approach based on over-riding the funding agreements should be adop
defaultted.
default  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe ‘academy chain’ model is very different from that of the ‘independent state school’ and it offers little scope for local democratic or strategic co-ordination or community governance.  It can fairly be said that schools in chains are not indepe
defaultndent, they just have different masters.
default&#xa0;
defaultContrary to much rhetoric, t
defaulthere is no convincing evidence that any particular type of school in terms of governance structure produces superior performance 
defaultagainst the 
defaultconventional
defaultly-accepted
default criteria.
default&#xa0;
defaultA new fram
defaultework is required in which trust and collaboration are emphasised and which spreads ownership to local communities and stakeholders within a pluralist multi-level system.  It is not right for the only significant democratic input to schooling to be at cent
defaultral level.
default&#xa0;
defaultAll publicly-funded schools should be placed within a common administrative and legal framework based on the principles of public not contract law.
default  Variations in levels of autonomy should be kept to an absolute minimum and fully justified as exceptions.
default  Various models including that of the maintained school trust should be considered.  An inclusive and integrated set of arrangements which avoids fa
defaultvouritism and unjustified hierarchies is required.   
default  
default  
